title: Client Report - Introduction
text:
Introduction



Elevator pitch
This metric measures the engines of cars that are made throughout the years making this data vital for any car manufacturer or even the everyday driver. It cannot be overstated how important it is for the everyday driver to know what his or her car is capable of. This data will also help car manufacture companies have more accurate marketting and give them a good idea of where their cars sit on the scale.


Read and format project data
# Include and execute your code here
df = pd.read_csv("https://github.com/byuidatascience/data4names/raw/master/data-raw/names_year/names_year.csv")




QUESTION|TASK 1
Finish the readings, setup, and be prepared with any questions to get your environment working smoothly (class for on-campus and Slack for online)
Yes, everything seems to work smoothly, this class still makes little sense and I barely made it out of this assignment with my sanity intact; it took forever to connect the dots of what I was both expected to do, and where to even start.


plot example
# Include and execute your code here

# Sample code built into the project, but as the only thing needed is a "Yes everything works fine." Having an example graph to prove it isn't a bad idea.

    x="name", 
    y="AK"
)
chart


                                                
My useless chart




QUESTION|TASK 2
In VS Code, create the example chart from section 3.2.2 of the textbook. (Note: you will be using Plotly Express to display the chart instead of Altair which is used in the book)
The results seem to go downwards in terms of “hwy” but then become scattered as “displ” gets better


Read and format data
# Include and execute your code here

# The actual code sample that I wrote to display a scatter plot of the graph represented in the textbook section 3.2.2 

# If I did this wrong or I'm using the project0.qmd file incorrectly please let me know, everyone on Slack is being irresponsive and I'm struggling to make sense of this class.


url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/byuidatascience/data4python4ds/master/data-raw/mpg/mpg.csv" # We get these values from a csv file online

mpg = pd.read_csv(url) # We load those values into a variable and then convert it to a chart using plotly.
px.scatter(mpg, x=mpg.displ, y=mpg.hwy)
